.com/magicmonty/bash-git-prompt/refs/heads/master/gitprompt.sh\n\nexplain_prompt = f\"\"\"\nPlease explain what this file does at a very high level. What is it, and why would I use it?\n\n```\n{file_contents}\n```\n\"\"\"\n\nresponse = client.models.generate_content(\n    model='gemini-2.5-flash',\n    contents=explain_prompt)\n\nMarkdown(response.text)","metadata":{"id":"7_jPMMoxkIEb","trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-04-05T03:25:12.544389Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-04-05T03:25:12.545086Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-04-05T03:25:23.713528Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-04-05T03:25:12.545049Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-04-05T03:25:23.712556Z"}},"outputs":[{"execution_count":52,"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":"<IPython.core.display.Markdown object>","text/markdown":"This file is a **Bash/Zsh script** designed to enhance your command-line experience by providing a highly customizable and informative shell prompt.\n\nAt a very high level:\n\n*   **What it is:** It's a set of shell functions and configurations written in Bash (with Zsh compatibility) that dynamically generates your command-line prompt (`PS1`).\n*   **What it does:** It integrates various pieces of information directly into your terminal prompt, primarily focusing on the status of your Git repository and your current programming environment.\n\n---\n\n### Why would you use it?\n\nYou would use this script to get **instant, visual feedback** about your development context directly in your terminal, which can significantly boost your productivity and help prevent mistakes.\n\nHere's a breakdown of the key information it provides and why that's useful:\n\n1.  **Git Repository Status:**\n    *   **Current Branch/Tag:** Always know which Git branch you're on, or if you're in a \"detached HEAD\" state.\n    *   **Local Changes:** See at a glance if you have:\n        *   Staged changes (ready to commit).\n        *   Unstaged changes (modified files not yet added to the staging area).\n        *   Conflicted files (from a merge or rebase).\n        *   Untracked files (new files not yet added to Git).\n        *   Stashed changes.\n    *   **Remote Status:** It can tell you if your local branch is ahead of or behind its remote counterpart, indicating if you need to push or pull. It even fetches remote status in the background so this information stays current.\n    *   **Repository Name:** Optionally displays the Git repository name.\n\n2.  **Virtual Environment Awareness:**\n    *   It automatically detects and displays the name of your active virtual environments (e.g., Python `venv`, Node.js, Conda environments). This is crucial for ensuring you're working in the correct isolated environment.\n\n3.  **Last Command Status:**\n    *   It shows an indicator (e.g., a color change or a symbol) if the previous command you ran failed or succeeded. This is a quick way to know if something went wrong without having to explicitly check the exit code.\n\n4.  **Customization and Theming:**\n    *   You can customize the appearance of your prompt, including colors, symbols, and the order of information. It supports different themes and allows you to create your own.\n\nIn essence, instead of manually typing `git status`, `git branch`, or checking which `venv` is active, this script makes that crucial information **visible in your prompt at all times**, helping you stay informed and efficient."},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":52},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Learn more\n\nTo learn more about prompting in depth:\n\n* Check out the whitepaper issued with today's content,\n* Try out the apps listed at the top of this notebook ([TextFX](https://textfx.withgoogle.com/), [SQL Talk](https://sql-talk-r5gdynozbq-uc.a.run.app/) and [NotebookLM](https://notebooklm.google/)),\n* Read the [Introduction to Prompting](https://ai.google.dev/gemini-api/docs/prompting-intro) from the Gemini API docs,\n* Explore the Gemini API's [prompt gallery](https://ai.google.dev/gemini-api/prompts) and try them out in AI Studio,\n* Check out the Gemini API cookbook for [inspirational examples](https://github.com/google-gemini/cookbook/blob/main/examples/) and [educational quickstarts](https://github.com/google-gemini/cookbook/blob/main/quickstarts/).\n\nBe sure to check out the codelabs on day 3 too, where you will explore some more advanced prompting with code execution.\n\nAnd please share anything exciting you have tried in the Discord!\n\n*- [Mark McD](https://linktr.ee/markmcd)*","metadata":{"id":"2a8266d97ce5"}}]}